<h2> Formation </h2>


<h2> Definition </h2>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
The @HI{{@EM{{ikutsu}}}} is used to ask "how many" about things that are counted with
<a href="grammar-counter-tsu.html">@HI{{tsu}}</a>.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      A: @HI{{mikanwo,@EM{{ikutsu}}@KJ{{buy}}imashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      B: @HI{{@FG{{8:yaxtsu}}tsu@KJ{{buy}}imashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      A: How many oranges did you buy?
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I bought eight.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
The @HI{{@EM{{nan'}}}} is used with a counter to ask for "how many" for things counted with that counter.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{kono@KJ{{meeting^company}}ni@KJ{{outside^country^person}}ga@EM{{@KJ{{what^person}}}}imasuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      How many foreigners are there in this company?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
The @HI{{@EM{{donogurai-}}}} is used to ask about the length of time something takes.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@EM{{donogurai}} @KJ{{day^book^word}}wo @KJ{{exertion^strong}}shimashitaka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      How long did you study Japanese?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
The @HI{{@EM{{gurai-}}}} is added after quantifiers to mean "about" or "approximately".

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{study^exam}}ni @KJ{{before^life}}ga 30@KJ{{person}}@EM{{gurai}} imasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      There are about 30 teachers in our school.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

